

<p>The <b>Construction Management Abstracts</b> site is a database of titles, authors, abstracts, and keywords. We bring together material from a wide range of sources: leading journals in construction management, recent ARCOM Conference Proceedings, and PhD theses.</p>
<p>Academic study in this field can be challenging to navigate. Construction is typically a technical or scientific subject, while management draws on social sciences such as organization studies, economics, and law. Construction management sits at the intersection of these traditions, creating new opportunities for using social science to understand and reflect on the construction sector. While new insights are developed for both social sciences and construction science, this combination can also make it harder to locate relevant literature, especially for those new to the field or working across disciplinary boundaries.</p> 
